heir value in helping businesses stay agile and responsive to rapid shifts =
in demand, and how products like Broad Match leverage LLMs to match ads to =
relevant searches and help advertisers respond to what millions of people a=
re searching for. This is foundational. As advances accelerate in our under=
lying AI models, our ability to help businesses find users at speed and sca=
le and drive ROI just keeps getting better. We=E2=80=99re especially excite=
d about the doors Gen AI=E2=80=99s opening for creative capabilities, helpi=
ng deliver on the premise of getting the right ad to the right user in the =
right moment.

This really is a big deal, for both Google and Meta, even if it is mostly b=
eneath the surface or only visible to advertisers; it is also an advantage =
that will separate both companies from their digital advertising rivals.

* The real monetization question, though, is about search, and Pichai argue=
d that Google deserved the benefit of the doubt that the company would figu=
re it out:

Well, the first question on Search, not much more to add to what I said but=
 what we have seen, and remember we=E2=80=99ve been in live experiments jus=
t for a few weeks in the U .S. and U.K. and on a slice of our queries where=
, and all indications are positive that it improves user satisfaction. We s=
ee an increase in engagement, but I see this as something which will play o=
ut over time.

But if you were to step back this moment there were a lot of questions last=
 year, and we always felt confident and comfortable that we would be able t=
o improve the user experience. People question whether these things would b=
e costly to serve, and we are very, very confident. We can manage the cost =
of how to serve these queries. People worried about latency. I think we are=
, when I look at the progress we have made in latency and efficiency, we fe=
el comfortable. There are questions about monetization, and based on our te=
sting so far, I am comfortable and confident that we=E2=80=99ll be able to =
manage the monetization transition here well as well. It will play out over=
 time, but I feel we are well positioned, and more importantly, when I look=
 at the innovation that=E2=80=99s ahead and the way the teams are working h=
ard on it, I am very excited about the future ahead.

It is harder to trust Google than Meta, in part because the latter is found=
er-led and the former is not. I think, though, that Pichai makes a fair arg=
ument: Google is bringing its advantages to bear in a much more tangible wa=
y, and is laying the groundwork for more.

Google=E2=80=99s Re-Org
---------------

The point I skipped in Pichai=E2=80=99s list was =E2=80=9Cvelocity in execu=
tion=E2=80=9D. Here was Pichai=E2=80=99s argument:

We=E2=80=99ve been really focused on simplifying our structures to help us =
move faster. In addition to bringing together our model building teams unde=
r Google DeepMind, we recently unified our ML infrastructure and ML develop=
er teams to enable faster decisions, smarter compute allocation, and a bett=
er customer experience. Earlier this year, we brought our Search teams toge=
ther under one leader. And last week, we took another step bringing togethe=
r our platforms and devices teams. The new combined team will focus on deli=
vering high quality products and experiences, bolstering the Android and Ch=
rome ecosystems, and bringing our best innovations to partners faster. We a=
lso remain focused on long-term efforts to durably re-engineer our cost bas=
e. You can see the impact of this work reflected in our operating market. W=
e continue to manage our headcount growth and align teams with our highest =
priority areas.

=E2=80=9CLast week=E2=80=9D was a reference to a pretty significant re-orga=
nization that Pichai announced on Google=E2=80=99s blog ( https://blog.goog=
le/inside-google/company-announcements/building-ai-future-april-2024/ ). Th=
ere are three notable points about the announcement.

First, while Google=E2=80=99s initial response to ChatGPT was to combine Go=
ogle Brain and DeepMind into one organization, this re-organization brings =
in Google Research and the Responsible AI teams to the same organization. I=
t=E2=80=99s pretty amazing, and speaks to Google=E2=80=99s internal dysfunc=
tion, that all of these teams were broadly speaking doing the same thing in=
 multiple different organizations, but that is why competition is important=
! What is particularly notable, though, is the inclusion of Responsible AI.=
 I suspect this is a response to the Gemini roll-out disaster that saw a ve=
ry capable model made to look ridiculous by Google=E2=80=99s safety teams; =
now those teams report to the same boss as the model makers.

Second (and to skip to the end for a moment) it=E2=80=99s notable that the =
announcement included a paragraph on Google being mission first:

One final note: All of the changes referenced above will help us work with =
greater focus and clarity towards our mission. However, we also need to be =
more focused in how we work, collaborate, discuss and even disagree. We hav=
e a culture of vibrant, open discussion that enables us to create amazing p=
roducts and turn great ideas into action. That=E2=80=99s important to prese=
rve. But ultimately we are a workplace and our policies and expectations ar=
e clear: this is a business, and not a place to act in a way that disrupts =
coworkers or makes them feel unsafe, to attempt to use the company as a per=
sonal platform, or to fight over disruptive issues or debate politics. This=
 is too important a moment as a company for us to be distracted.

This at first glance seems like a clear reference to the Google employees w=
ho were protesting in Google=E2=80=99s offices, and were subsequently (and =
rightly) fired. There was one more paragraph, though:

We have a duty to be an objective and trusted provider of information that =
serves all of our users globally. When we come to work, our goal is to orga=
nize the world=E2=80=99s information and make it universally accessible and=
 useful. That supersedes everything else and I expect us to act with a focu=
s that reflects that.

I think this is about more than that one incident, or, to put it another wa=
y, if it=E2=80=99s about one incident it too is about the Gemini brouhaha. =
As I=E2=80=99ve noted ( https://stratechery.com/2024/gemini-and-googles-cul=
ture/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3=
J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxp=
bmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczo=
vL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDI0L2dlbWluaS1hbmQtZ29vZ2xlcy1jdWx0dXJlLyJdfSwiZX=
hwIjoxNzE3MDc3NzcwLCJpYXQiOjE3MTQ0ODU3NzAsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc3Nwb=
3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldDpy=
ZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQgZW50aXRsZW1lbnRzIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZjF=
mQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2VzcyJ9.aCqwTX_4rE1a65NOoH7SpzAeAZ2gLAmnLgND98Nj-XRj6=
emYDax0h4bBltVO9vYdECrinNNKU1ghZVUMV-Ah2h_V-W48XPwhAtsfhXvXtPOkpCBIH20gSPE7=
MwRYcJtXpGpW08xxoVyc9fRrLJjRIDpnpX8C80d-BDdXUw6iSmhgbs2pRCTx4t1s39CYSdMG29J=
sBKdAWsK4CnkwFVpfOf0Z3R7rAufk8QcDPgcNajm7EdqMXnBDppTZ9R_gVQxDmODgke4wi1DToF=
FV-BRfPnsDy75oWxPSxhbeD6W-p2IyTn9m3dhbm5Z3UTEEMaaY5OJIrJaz3m9_Q-2p2dg7PQ ) =
, I think it was extremely bad for Google that its culture ever got to the =
point that Gemini shipped as it was; Pichai apparently agrees (and probably=
 hopes no one remembers who was ultimately responsible for that).

Google=E2=80=99s True Moonshot
----------------------

Finally, all of Google=E2=80=99s consumer platforms, including Android and =
Chrome, are being brought into the same organization under the leadership o=
f Rick Osterloh, the current head of Pixel. This seems like a very big deal=
! Google has long sought to assure its Android hardware partners that its P=
ixel division doesn=E2=80=99t get any special advantages when it comes to A=
ndroid; it=E2=80=99s going to be hard to say that with a straight face goin=
g forward.

I also think it=E2=80=99s the right move. Pichai said in the announcement, =
=E2=80=9CTo truly drive computing forward, we need to do it at the intersec=
tion of hardware, software and AI=E2=80=9D, and I completely agree. Indeed,=
 if you think about it, that is exactly what Google is doing everywhere els=
e: it=E2=80=99s ability to leverage AI in its products is interconnected wi=
th its hardware advantage in infrastructure; to do the same thing in phones=
 in the most effective way possible means actually making the phone.

This raises the most interesting question of all: is Google going for it=E2=
=80=99s true moonshot ( https://stratechery.com/2023/googles-true-moonshot/=
?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9=
ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiL=
CJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0=
cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIzL2dvb2dsZXMtdHJ1ZS1tb29uc2hvdC8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTcxNzA=
3Nzc3MCwiaWF0IjoxNzE0NDg1NzcwLCJpc3MiOiJodHRwczovL2FwaS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbm=
Uvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZWQ6cmVhZCBhcnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ=
29yeTpyZWFkIGVudGl0bGVtZW50cyIsInN1YiI6IlJzZXVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1=
c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.fHllGXNEE68-ZVRJ2D_9WZ5zjpZXX_iEfYdaIE0C-jpJjhNnDVYEDjIg=
HtzJqVizAKPq3HPVFUHB8NNSxMEWlh9PCItlcgvbJgIY0oyfsvyNIEu_ran58H5wvne7Suvl4w5=
yXxgmDYoDmuul-jT3Gts9w5vAi4JGkE-VeF10AQXvmbQ2HveuOQZBLmwoNYTJNtej2oYJ5s2BUS=
e4r8NcKkVOyIuZ-G7PeZkhzfBOuWetdF0eAuDAuzF_x6l8Oa3iU-3vAwMEvNTuvCSUP92Z0eF3c=
M7idkxMeaSKeEfgFQHNgdx45WOvi4a1AHrOB57O992DUW2T-VX5fgDVQ5NDNA ) =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0actually taking Apple on in smartphones, not with a hardware ecosyste=
m, but rather its own devices? I wrote last year:

Google=E2=80=99s collection of moonshots =E2=80=94 from Waymo to Google Fib=
er to Nest to Project Wing to Verily to Project Loon (and the list goes on)=
 =E2=80=94 have mostly been science projects that have, for the most part, =
served to divert profits from Google Search away from shareholders. Waymo i=
s probably the most interesting, but even if it succeeds, it is ultimately =
a car service rather far afield from Google=E2=80=99s mission statement =E2=
=80=9Cto organize the world=E2=80=99s information and make it universally a=
ccessible and useful.=E2=80=9D

What, though, if the mission statement were the moonshot all along? What if=
 =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m Feeling Lucky=E2=80=9D were not a whimsical button on=
 a spartan home page, but the default way of interacting with all of the wo=
rld=E2=80=99s information? What if an AI Assistant were so good, and so nat=
ural, that anyone with seamless access to it simply used it all the time, w=
ithout thought?

That, needless to say, is probably the only thing that truly scares Apple. =
Yes, Android has its advantages to iOS, but they aren=E2=80=99t particularl=
y meaningful to most people, and even for those that care =E2=80=94 like me=
 =E2=80=94 they are not large enough to give up on iOS=E2=80=99s overall su=
perior user experience. The only thing that drives meaningful shifts in pla=
tform marketshare are paradigm shifts, and while I doubt the v1 version of =
Pixie [Google=E2=80=99s rumored Pixel-only AI assistant] would be good enou=
gh to drive switching from iPhone users, there is at least a path to where =
it does exactly that.

Of course Pixel would need to win in the Android space first, and that woul=
d mean massively more investment by Google in go-to-market activities in pa=
rticular, from opening stores to subsidizing carriers to ramping up product=
ion capacity. It would not be cheap, which is why it=E2=80=99s no surprise =
that Google hasn=E2=80=99t truly invested to make Pixel a meaningful player=
 in the smartphone space.

The potential payoff, though, is astronomical: a world with Pixie everywher=
e means a world where Google makes real money from selling hardware, in add=
ition to services for enterprises and schools, and cloud services that leve=
rage Google=E2=80=99s infrastructure to provide the same capabilities to bu=
sinesses. Moreover, it=E2=80=99s a world where Google is truly integrated: =
the company already makes the chips, in both its phones and its data center=
s, it makes the models, and it does it all with the largest collection of d=
ata in the world.

Google has a very long ways to go to make this a reality, or, frankly, to e=
ven make it a corporate goal. It will cost a lot of money, risk partnership=
s, and lower margins. It is, though, a massive opportunity =E2=80=94 the ma=
ximal application of AI to Google=E2=80=99s business prospects =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0and it strikes me as a pretty big deal that, at least when it comes to t=
he org chart, the Pixel has been elevated above Android.

